name: (2E)-3-(5-bromofuran-2-yl)-1-furan-2-ylprop-2-en-1-one
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-1178
Reason: The base compound furan has a melting point of around -6 degrees Celsius. The bromine substituent increases the melting point due to its increased molecular weight and polarity. The furan ring itself contributes to the melting point due to its planarity and increased molecular weight. The presence of a second furan ring adds additional polarity and planarity, which can contribute to the melting point. The presence of a methyl group on the alpha carbon can also contribute to the melting point due to its increased molecular weight and polarity. The bromine on the alpha carbon can also contribute to the melting point due to its increased molecular weight and polarity.
